Functionality testing:

1. To test the functionality, I added several directories.  
2. To these directories, I added several files.
3. Ran 'ip addr' command to retrieve the IPv4 address.  Then Returned
        to the Host machine and opened PowerShell and established a remote
        connection using the 'SSH username@IPv4' command and entered the password.
4. From the remote connection, I pinged the Ubuntu Server to verify connectivity.
5. Added a directory with a subdirectory, and added a file to this subdirectory.
6. Created a symbolic link from my user directory pointing to the file in the 
        in the subdirectory.
7. Created a file in another directory and created a hard link in the user 
        directory for this new file.
8. Added content to the file and verified the hard link reflected the changed content.
9. Returned to the server terminal and became root. Then added a file to one of
        the user directories. Then used 'setfacl' command to add read and write 
        permissions for my user account.  Used 'getfacl' command to verify the 
        changes were made.
10. Returned to remote terminal, and used 'echo "some text" >> fileName' to add
        content to the file.
11. Returned to the server terminal and verified the changes were made in the
        file. Then added some more text in the file.
12. From the remote terminal, verified that those changes were retrievable from
        from ACL user account.
13. From the server initiated the shutdown and monitored the remote terminal.
        Verified the message was sent from root of a scheduled shutdown.  Then 
        received a 'connection closed' message. At which time PowerShell returned to 
        its regular state on the Host OS.  